President Barack Obama has declared May 2013 as National Building Safety Month in the United States. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of robust building codes and standards in protecting American lives during natural disasters and other hazards. It also highlights the role of energy-efficient buildings in ensuring resilience. The President encourages citizens, government agencies, businesses, nonprofits, and other groups to participate in activities that raise awareness about building safety. The administration is collaborating with experts to provide modern guidance on construction and retrofitting techniques and supporting disaster preparedness, mitigation, and redevelopment efforts across the country. The proclamation calls on Americans to learn more about how they can contribute to building safety in their homes and communities.